you are trying to put two values (2 and 9) with the same key (1), but the HashMap will only keep the last value (9) for the key 1.

If you want to represent a tree-like structure with multiple children for each node, using a HashMap directly may not be suitable. Instead, you can use a different data structure to represent the tree. One approach could be to use a HashMap with Integer as keys and Lists of Integers as values, where each key represents a node, and the list contains all its child nodes.

You can do it like this

    Map&lt;Integer, List&lt;Integer&gt;&gt; numberInput = new HashMap&lt;&gt;();
    numberInput.put(1, new ArrayList&lt;&gt;());
    numberInput.get(1).add(2);
    numberInput.get(1).add(9);
    numberInput.put(2, new ArrayList&lt;&gt;());
    numberInput.get(2).add(3);
    numberInput.put(7, new ArrayList&lt;&gt;());
    numberInput.get(7).add(8);

    int[][] matrix = new int[10][10];
    for (int i = 1; i &lt;= matrix.length; i++) {
        List&lt;Integer&gt; children = numberInput.get(i);
        if (children != null) {
            for (int j : children) {
                matrix[i - 1][j - 1] = 1;
            }
        }
    }

I think the flaw is with your approach. The key of the Hashmap should be the location in your Matrix because that will be unique.

If we are using locations in serial i.e. (1,1) is referred as 1, and (1,2) is referred as 2 and (2,1) is referred as 3 than we can use location as key.


    Map&lt;Integer,Integer&gt; numberInput = new HashMap&lt;Integer,Integer&gt;();
      numberInput.put(2,1);
      numberInput.put(9,1);
      numberInput.put(3,2);
      numberInput.put(8,7);

If we are setting in accurate fashion of matrix i.e. (2,1) = 3, we can use (2,1) as string

    Map&lt;String,Integer&gt; numberInput = new HashMap&lt;String,Integer&gt;();
      numberInput.put(&quot;2,1&quot;,1);
      numberInput.put(&quot;2,2&quot;,1);

This way is more efficient and you will be able to fetch values by location.
Moreover, if you pass a duplicate key it will &quot;update&quot; the value, which make sense for the case.

